JAVA-01
Approaching Fibonacci
Easy
Problem Statement
Given a number N, find the closest Fibonacci number to N. If two Fibonacci numbers are equidistant, return the smaller one. Also implement a check: is a given number Fibonacci or not?
Example
Input: N = 14
Output: 13 (Fibonacci numbers near 14 are 13 and 21)
Input: N = 10
Output: 8 (8 and 13 are equidistant → return smaller = 8)
Full Solution
import java.util.*;

public class FibonacciApproach {

    // Check if a number is a perfect square
    static boolean isPerfectSquare(long n) {
        long sq = (long) Math.sqrt(n);
        return sq * sq == n;
    }

    // A number is Fibonacci if 5n²+4 or 5n²-4 is a perfect square
    static boolean isFibonacci(int n) {
        return isPerfectSquare(5L * n * n + 4) ||
               isPerfectSquare(5L * n * n - 4);
    }

    // Find closest Fibonacci number to N
    static int closestFibonacci(int n) {
        int a = 0, b = 1;
        while (b < n) {
            int temp = a + b;
            a = b;
            b = temp;
        }
        // b >= n, a is the Fibonacci just below n
        if (b - n <= n - a) return b;
        return a;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(closestFibonacci(14)); // 13
        System.out.println(closestFibonacci(10)); // 8
        System.out.println(isFibonacci(13));          // true
        System.out.println(isFibonacci(14));          // false
    }
}
How It Works
Key insight: Walk the Fibonacci sequence until you overshoot N. Now you have the Fibonacci just BELOW (a) and just ABOVE (b). Compare distances: if b-n <= n-a, b is closer; otherwise a is closer. The "is Fibonacci" check uses the golden ratio math property — no loops needed.